I am not skilled when it comes to creating things in the analogue world, my strength lies in the digital universe. (See my website http://www.baseggio.com to get an idea what I mean by that.) That's why I was mesmerised, when I saw a 3D printer for the first time, somewhen in the mid-nineties; a huge thing they used at ETH Zurich to prototype architecture designs. Ever since it was my dream to be able to use this kind of infrastructure myself one day. In the last few years prices have dropped dramatically, which allowed me to provide myself with a Delta Tower Printer (http://www.deltatower.ch) in early summer 2013. This fine machine allows me to bring my digital ideas to real, tangible life. I could not care less about the current hype and I do not know whether 3D printing will change the world or not. All I know is that a very personal dream of mine has come true.

Makerbot R2 heavily modified with full enclosure and all aluminum upgrades from plastic. Also heated glass build plate. Can print in ABS, PLA, or Nylon. Use Garnier Fructese number 5 extreme hold hairspray on the glass for holding parts in place. 60 degrees C for PLA and 100 Degrees C for ABS. Outstanding. No more tape!

I use Keycreater for design work, and Simplify 3D for slicing and printing. Sailfish firmware on my R2. If you have a replicator and you aren't using sailfish and simplify 3D you are missing out. Check it out. Amazing software. Way beyond makerware. Best $140 I ever spent wrt to 3D printing. On the Taz 5 I am using rcbugfix branch of Marlin. Aaron Forrester was born in Rockford, IL but lived most of his life in Southern California; namely San Diego. Although Aaron visited San Diego Comic-Con while he lived near by, it wasn't until he moved to Phoenix, AZ when he started to become interested in costume and prop making. Up until that point, Aaron loved going all out for Halloween and was active in musical theater, drama, community theater, film and television. In 2007 Aaron started to work as Manager for Atomic Comics in Chandler, AZ. It was there that he was introduced to groups such as the Rebel Legion and the 501st. It was the combination of those groups and one of his staff that inspired him to take his talent beyond costuming for Halloween. Although Aaron had made costumes in years prior, it was the first time that he had decided to do something on a large scale. It was at that point Aaron built his first suit of armor based on the movie armor of Iron Man. From that point onward, he went onto founding the Arizona Avengers charity costuming club and subsequently its sister chapters; West Coast Avengers, East Coast Avengers, Mid Pacific Avengers. For the past 5 years, Aaron has also been the costuming director for the Amazing Arizona Comic Con, Amazing Las Vegas Comic Con, and the upcoming Amazing Hawaii Comic-Con. In addition to his role as Costuming Director, Aaron has also been a costume contest judge multiple times including a cosplay consultant and judge for Salt Lake Comic Con and Salt Lake FanX. When Aaron is not working on costumes or doing charity work with the Arizona Avengers, he enjoys spending time with his loved ones and at Disneyland.

Anyway more about my printer experience and some boasting:
PLA prints nice but for strong print you'll need 220 degrees or higher.
For ABS I use 250 to 270 degrees. That may sound pretty high, and it is. ABS melts at 190 but around 230 degrees it prints okay. Every filament is different.
With my AnetA8 I went from 30mm/s, to 60mm/s, to 120mm/s.
I have tried 150mm/s but that gave me extrusion problems. Occasionally 120mm/s also give me extrusion issues, but that depends on the flow, retraction, re-prime and retraction speed. Actually the AnetA8 actually cannot reach print speeds of 120 mm/s or higher due to the Print Jerk and Print travel speed settings. You can edit these in Marlin or in the slicer Cura. I use 4000 mm/s^2 and 40 mm/2. My retraction is 40mm/s or 60 mm/s. In Simplify3D I use 120mm/s and edit the speed per; initial layer, outer layer, brim or infill.

Also I should edit my skynet 3D marlin settings. Check out their Facebook page for the latest releases, there is support for auto bed level sensors and a news graphical display screen.

bio:
Decades of 3d experience, both for cg and for CNC machining. Mostly a software developer with an eye for design who started an e-cig business because he wanted something fun to do. 3D Printing comes in handy as a way to quickly prototype items that are impractical to make by hand.

Besides my day job as a software developer for Mirada Studios, I'm also developing a couple brands of high end e-cig merchandise - designed using the tools I'm familiar with, prototyped using 3d Printing, and manufactured in CNC and traditional investment casting methods usually reserved for jewelry. Later in 2015, I'm also planning to apply this process to creating special accessories for sailing and boating.

I believe that everything should be beautiful - that functional items can be ornate and extravagant, and that recent advances in technology means there's no excuse for ordinary items not also being beautiful. I still make functional items that are merely functional, but I try to keep even the simple ones "pretty".

For my Things, expect to see mostly functional tools for 3d printing and cnc milling - most of my more interesting items are supposed to be commercial so I keep the files to myself, but when I have something useful that I don't want to manufacture commercially it will absolutely appear here. I may also make some of these items available over on Shapeways for folks who would rather devote their print time to things they're personally invested in, or who want them in materials that it's often impractical to print in unless you're a commercial prototyping service.

BuMatics Desgins® ( Dr. Ann Karmos, a retired math educator/professor, came by one day, reviewed my designs and ideas, and suggested the name "BuMatics." I think it is a sweet name for what I have been playing around in teaching and learning math. I believe that students' understanding or lack of understanding of mathematics is closely grounded in their experiences in the broad context of culture, context, and tool or model use. As we bring meaningful and playful mathematical activities to children, they are more likely to see and enjoy mathematics in the way it really is!

Well, I am a STEAM educator, learning from and working with K-12 STEAM teachers to explore new ideas of teaching and engagement. I firmly believe ART is at the core of STEM learning or all human learning! I owe my ideas and designs to the hundreds of K-12 children and teachers and university professors I have had the pleasure of working with, in multiple disciplines-- math, science,engineering language arts, social studies, early childhood education and more! All mistakes, of course, are mine!

There is no warranty or liability whatsoever implied or explicit behind the designs or ideas. They are all posted for their potential educational values. When working with children, please strictly observe all safety and health procedures! Please refer to the NSTA safety guides: http://www.nsta.org/safety/. I appreciate your visit and support. I can rip video game files pretty easily, and I've had a 3d printer for a little bit over a year now. I can provide advice on issues you may be having regarding leveling, axis warping, heated warping, filament grinding, fan noises, inconsistent filament, etc. I've been through the learning curve and I know what I'm talking about. I'm also in a 3d printing club at my high school and have several friends that do the same. I highly suggest getting a 3d pen for like 20 bucks to use for sticking models together, fixing little errors in prints, and just to play around with. Also I've tried about 7 brands of filament and Fugetech seemed to be the cheapest that worked well with no issues. And don't use ABS until you get good at leveling and know what changes you'll have to make in the settings. Don't get intimated by ABS though, just read up on it or you can contact me and I'll give you advice.

Cyber-NY is a digital agency located in the Flatiron District of New York City. Founded in 1996 as a technology and media innovator, we continue to be passionate about emerging technologies and the interaction between art, commerce and technology. We work with UX design, web / app and social media development and have been fortunate to work with some top agencies and brands in NYC and throughout the world.

Currently in the lab at Cyber-NY, we have our Solidoodle SD3 working overtime producing everything from HD Camera Rockets to Robotic Claws. We're big fans of 3D printing, design and the direction of this industry. We don't know where it will take us but are certainly enjoying the ride! Visit us at http://www.cyber-ny.com.
